In this case, they&#x27;re meant to be as simple as possible and the individual field-views can do whatever they prefer, as they&#x27;re the ones rendering them. The parent form only gets a `valid: true` and a `value` from the child. Since these are error messages meant to be used directly as error messages to users, it didn&#x27;t seem like a big gain to do anything more.<p>With regard to &quot;pain in the butt to extend&quot; you could use `extend` and just replace that one method that returns those string, right?<p>InputView.extend({
  getErrorMessage: function () {
    // return error objects instead?
  }
})<p>/me shrugs<p>Forms really are a pain, we tried to create a simple contract between a form-view an it&#x27;s child field views that was as flexible as possible so you could easily write more input types.<p>More on that contract here: <a href="http://ampersandjs.com/learn/forms#form-input-view-conventions" rel="nofollow">http://ampersandjs.com/learn/forms#form-input-view-conventio...</a><p>But hey, also... easy enough to use something else entirely, it&#x27;s not like the forms stuff is bundled :)
